@node Login Screen Desktop and Terminal
@chapter Login Screen, Desktop and Terminal
Examples are given with Ubuntu Linux. Other Linux distributions should be
similar.

@section Login Screen
@cindex Login Screen
Start the Linux computer and it will proceed to the login screen.
@*
@*
@center @image{images/LoginScreenCropped-960x576,12.5cm,7.5cm,Login Screen Linux,png}
@*
@*
Select the user name and enter the password.
@*
@*
@center @image{images/LoginScreenPasswordCropped-960x576,12.5cm,7.5cm,Login Screen Linux,png}

@section Desktop
@cindex Desktop
The Linux desktop will display.
@*
@*
@center @image{images/Desktop-960x576,,200pt,Desktop Linux Screen,png}
@*
@*
@center @image{images/2-960x576,,140pt,Picture of Bella,jpg}

@section Terminal
@cindex Terminal
We will proceed to open a Linux terminal. On the upper left hand side of the screen select Activities.
@*
@*
@center @image{images/Activities,,100pt,Activies,png}
@*
@*
A input box saying ``Type To Search'' box will appear.
@*
@*
@center @image{images/TypeToSearch,12cm,2.5cm,Type To Search,png}
@*
@*
Inside the ``Type To Search'' input box type the word Terminal.
@*
@*
@center @image{images/TypeToSearchTerminal,12cm,3.5cm,Activies,png}
@*
@*
The Linux terminal will appear. The terminal is also known as the Linux Shell or the command line.
@*
@*
@center @image{images/Terminal-960x576,12cm,7cm,Image of the Linux Terminal,png}
@*
@*
@center @image{images/3-960x576,,140pt,Picture of Bella,jpg}
@*
@*
Congratulations! You have logged into Linux and opened a terminal on the desktop! The Linux Terminal is a command language interpreter that executes commands read from your input. In the next chapter we will execute some commands.

@node Linux Commands
@chapter Linux Commands
@cindex Linux Commands
@center @image{images/5-960x576,,180pt,Picture of Bella,jpg}
@section @command{whoami}
@cindex whoami
The command @command{whoami} prints your userid. At the Linux terminal type the command @command{whoami}.
@*
@*
@image{images/command-whoami,13cm,2cm,Example of Linux command whoami,png}
@*
@*
Linux responds that Bella is logged in. Your system should respond that your logged in by displaying your login name.

@section @command{ls}
@cindex ls
The command @command{ls} lists directory contents. At the Linux terminal type the command @command{ls}.
@*
@*
@image{images/command-ls,15cm,2cm,Example of Linux command ls,png}
@*
@*
We can see Bella has the following directories:
@*
Desktop, Documents, Downloads, Music, Pictures, Public, Templates, Videos.
@*
@*
Directories can also be called folders.
@*
@*
We can look inside an individual directory by giving command @command{ls} a specific
directory name to look in. Type: @command{ls Music}
@*
@*
@image{images/command-ls-Music,14cm,2cm,Example of Linux command ls on Music directory,png}
@*
@*
Looks like Bella has no music.
@*
@*
We can check if Bella has any documents. Type: @command{ls Documents}
@*
@*
@image{images/command-ls-Music-Documents,14cm,2.3cm,Example of Linux command ls on Documents directory,png}
@*
@*
Bella has no documents
@*
@*
@center @image{images/4-960x576,,180pt,Picture of Bella,jpg}

